node.title: 'People not heeding our advice': Some Tasmanians stuck in floodwaters as storms strike
node.description: Hobartians are mopping up this morning following thunderstorms that brought heavy rain and hail to the Tasmanian capital and parts of the state's south-east.

node.title: Elective surgery patients in Queensland may require COVID test
node.description: Elective surgery patients may require a negative COVID-19 test in the 72 hours before their procedures under options being discussed within Queensland Health to reduce the risk of hospital transmission.

node.title: Queenslanders in for a brief reprieve before more flooding set to hit sodden southern Queensland
node.description: As floodwaters recede and residents across southern Queensland clean up, the weather bureau warns isolated storms across already sodden catchment areas could lead to more flooding next week.

node.title: Myanmar junta cancels passports of high-profile opponents and shadow government figures
node.description: Myanmar's military junta revokes the passports of dozens of its leading opponents in an apparent attempt to stop them travelling and building international opposition to the regime.

node.title: MIQ rules could be changed to allow 501 deportees to stay longer
node.description: Corrections is urgently trying to change MIQ rules so New Zealanders deported from Australia can stay in hotels for longer.

node.title: Armed man in custody after standoff forces lockdown at UN headquarters
node.description: An armed man was taken into custody Thursday after an hours-long standoff with police forced the United Nations headquarters to go under lockdown in New York City, authorities said

node.title: Tennis Stars Praise WTA's Steve Simon for Peng Shuai Withdrawal
node.description: As women's tennis champions applauded Simon's actions, men's tennis stars demanded their organizations follow suit and take action against China.

node.title: Florida City Cancels Circus-Themed Ball for First Black Mayor After He Declines to Attend
node.description: Mayor-elect Ken Welch said in a statement that the ball was a learning opportunity for St. Petersburg, which was once segregated.

node.title: Nathan was once told he'd never run his own business — now he's doing it with the support of a major corporate
node.description: When Nathan Johnston was younger, people told him he was "dreaming" when he talked about starting his own business. But on International Day of People with Disability it becomes a reality, as he launches a social media platform he created from his dining room table.

node.title: Friday News Quiz: Rhianna, Trump and Katter were in the headlines this week. Only one was kicked out a bar
node.description: Will you be declared a national hero for your efforts or will you be unceremoniously thrown out? Test yourself to find out.

node.title: 'Moving towards COVID-normal': ACT to overhaul state of emergency laws, but don't expect Victorian-style protests
node.description: The ACT government says it will soon be hard to justify calling the ongoing pandemic a public health "emergency", and wants to move away from that language.

node.title: There were winners, losers and big losers amongst Australia's universities last year — and the 'big eight' didn't escape
node.description: Some universities actually increased revenue once the pandemic started, yet some vice-chancellors are deeply unhappy. The reasons why are complex, writes Conor Duffy.

node.title: An eight-hour year and hot enough to melt iron — this planet's 'not somewhere you'd want to go on holidays'
node.description: About 30 light-years away a rocky planet as dense as pure iron orbits a red dwarf star half the size of our Sun. A year on GJ 367 b is shorter than a day on Earth.

node.title: Germany considers COVID-19 vaccine mandate as cases surge
node.description: Germany bans unvaccinated people from non-essential stores and venues, and considers making vaccines mandatory as new case numbers hit 70,000 in 24 hours.

node.title: Rachelle Miller says she made her allegations about Alan Tudge not for revenge, but so that other women can be heard
node.description: It took a bruising year after Rachelle Miller first told her story about minister Alan Tudge for her to finally be heard, and for him to face consequences and stand aside, writes Louise Milligan.

node.title: IKEA to buy land near Sylvia Park in Auckland
node.description: Swedish-founded flatpack furniture giant IKEA is a step closer to setting up in New Zealand.

node.title: Why Hasn’t the U.S. Found More Omicron Cases?
node.description: Genomic surveillance has improved enormously in recent months, but the system has built-in delays, and blind spots remain.

node.title: Should Americans 'Upgrade' Face Coverings to Surgical Masks Amid Omicron Spread?
node.description: Some health experts recommend switching to surgical masks amid the little-known information about Omicron and its transmissibility.

node.title: Rural contractor recommends hiring young people to build workforce
node.description: Chapman Agriculture owner Allan Chapman says the labour shortage has forced him to look closer to home.

node.title: US reports first Omicron case
node.description: The United States has identified its first known case of the new Covid-19 variant Omicron, discovered in a fully vaccinated patient who traveled to South Africa.

node.title: Wool price making a comeback as overseas demand for products rises
node.description: Higher demand for sportswear, rugs and other wool products has resulted in a resurgence in wool prices.

node.title: Iron World Appears to Be Lightest Exoplanet Ever Detected
node.description: Astronomers call it a “super-Mercury” and think it holds clues to how planets form close in to their stars.

node.title: A Guide to New York Holiday Events: Trains, Nutcrackers and a 79-Foot Tree
node.description: A rundown of seasonal celebrations in every borough, including the return of the Rockettes, miniature trains in the Bronx and light shows in Brooklyn.

node.title: Sister of Condemned Man in Saudi Arabia Asks F1 Star Lewis Hamilton to Help Free Brother
node.description: The sister of a man on death row in Saudi Arabia for unwittingly being a drug mule asked Lewis Hamilton to speak about him at his upcoming F1 race.

node.title: Two Men Charged With Murder of Teen Shot 18 Times Waiting for Bus, Police to Arrest 3 More
node.description: Both men allegedly involved in the 14-year-old's death are at least 20 years old and police consider the case "solved."

node.title: Rep. Jim Jordan Faces Backlash After Tweet Stating 'Real America Is Done With COVID-19'
node.description: The Ohio Republican's message on Twitter was met with a large response, especially from critics.

node.title: Anti-Abortion Activists Arrested After Spending Hours Inside Clinic For 'Intervention'
node.description: At least one woman left the White Plains, New York clinic "in tears," according to the group Red Rose Rescue, which claimed responsibility for the incident.

node.title: U.S. Military Records Thousands of Missing Military-Grade Weapons, Including TNT, Rockets
node.description: The Associated Press has released a new report discussing the large amounts of explosives missing from the U.S. military.

node.title: SA has opened it borders to COVID, what can Tasmania learn from it?
node.description: South Australia is a little over a week into reopening their borders and what happens with COVID-19 infections — and the death rate — is being watched closely by Tasmania, where the island state is soon to open up to the world.

node.title: People in NSW have to vote tomorrow — this is what you need to know
node.description: Almost every NSW resident has to vote in one of the more than 120 elections set to be held tomorrow. This is what you need to know.
